{{Infobox language |name=Douala |states=[[Cameroon]] |ethnicity=[[Douala people|Douala]], [[Mungo people|Mungo]] |speakers={{sigfig|87,700|1}} |date=1982 |ref=e18 |speakers2=2 million L1 and L2 speakers in [[Douala]] (2013) |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam2=[[Atlantic–Congo languages|Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3=[[Benue–Congo languages|Benue–Congo]] |fam4=[[Southern Bantoid languages|Southern Bantoid]] |fam5=[[Bantu languages|Bantu]] ([[Bantu Zone A|Zone A]]) |fam6=[[Sawabantu languages|Sawabantu]] (A.20) |dia1=Duala proper |dia2=Bodiman |dia3=Oli (Ewodi, Wuri) |dia4=[[Pongo language|Pongo]] |dia5=Mongo (Muungo) |iso2=dua |iso3=dua |glotto=dual1243 |glottorefname=Duala |guthrie=A.24–26 }} {{Infobox language |name=Jo |states=[[Cameroon]] |region=around [[Douala]] |speakers=none |familycolor=Pidgin |family=Douala-based pidgin |iso3=none |glotto=none |guthrie=A.20A }}
'''Duala''' (also spelt '''Douala''', '''Diwala''', '''Dwela''', '''Dualla''' and '''Dwala''') is a [[dialect cluster]] spoken by the [[Duala people|Duala]] and [[Mungo people]]s of [[Cameroon]]. Douala belongs to the [[Bantu languages|Bantu language family]], in a subgroup called [[Sawabantu languages|Sawabantu]]. Maho (2009) treats Douala as a cluster of five languages: Douala proper, Bodiman, Oli (Ewodi, Wuri), [[Pongo language|Pongo]] and Mongo. He also notes a Douala-based pidgin named ''Jo''.
== Popular culture == The song "[[Soul Makossa]]", as well as pop songs that repeated its lyrics, internationally popularised the Duala word for "(I) dance", "makossa".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inst.at/trans/13Nr/echu13.htm |title=TRANS Nr. 13: George Echu (Yaounde): Multilingualism as a Resource: the Lexical Appropriation of Cameroon Indigenous Languages by English and French |website=Inst.at |date= |accessdate=2017-07-06}}</ref> The song [[Alane (song)|Alane]] by artist [[Wes Madiko]] is sung in Duala and reached #1 position in over 9 European countries.
