[[File:Wappen der Schriftgiesser.jpg|thumb|The German coat of arms for a type-founders' guild (or "Schriftgießer" in German)]] A '''type foundry''' is a [[company]] that [[Type design|designs]] or distributes [[typeface]]s. Before desktop publishing, type foundries manufactured and sold metal and wood typefaces and [[Matrix (printing)|matrices]] for line-casting machines like the [[Linotype machine|Linotype]] and [[Monotype System|Monotype]] machines designed to be used with [[Letterpress printing|letterpress]] printers. Today's [[typeface|digital type]] foundries accumulate and distribute typefaces (typically as [[Computer font|digitized fonts]]) created by [[type designer]]s, who may either be [[freelancer]]s operating their own independent foundry, or employed by another foundry. Type foundries may also provide custom type design services.
In England, type foundries began in 1476, when [[William Caxton]] introduced the [[printing press]]. Thereafter the [[City of London]] became a major centre for the industry, until the end of the 20th century when famous metal-based printing districts such as [[Fleet Street]] came to the close of their era. The industry was particularly important in [[Victorian era|Victorian times]], when education became available to all due to the new school boards, and firms such as [[Charles Reed (British politician)|Charles Reed & Sons]], the printer and type founders were in their heyday. The [[St Bride Printing Library]] in the City of London encourages wider public interest in the history of type founding for the printed book and newspaper.
